            " PROJECT DECLARATION\n",
            "==================================================\n",
            "Scenario: Customer Support\n",
            "Topic: TechGadgets Online Store\n",
            "Description: A tool to help you pick out the best adapter for your laptop.\n",
            "Target Users: Tech newbies, Min-Max enthusiasts, and Deal Hunters\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "avVTR38z0t7b"
      },
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Part 3: Create Your Knowledge Base\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the foundation of your RAG system. Create comprehensive, well-organized documents for your chosen scenario.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Guidelines for Good Knowledge Base Documents:\n",
        "- **Be specific**: Include names, numbers, dates, and concrete details\n",
        "- **Be comprehensive**: Cover the topic thoroughly\n",
        "- **Be organized**: Structure information logically\n",
        "- **Be accurate**: Ensure facts are correct and consistent across documents"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "7HoXfIsp0t7b",
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "outputId": "16eda8e1-5d60-430c-d8d9-96a48c8a8c34"
      },
      "source": [
        "# ============================================================\n",
        "# TODO: Create your knowledge base with at least 8 documents\n",
        "# ============================================================\n",
        "\n",
        "# Each document should have:\n",
        "# - A clear, descriptive key (used as document ID)\n",
        "# - Content of at least 150 words\n",
        "# - Specific, factual information\n",
        "\n",
        "knowledge_base = {\n",
        "    # EXAMPLE FORMAT (replace with your own content):\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_1\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Voltage and Wattage Specifications]\n",
        "\n",
        "    Laptop adapters must match the original power requirements exactly to ensure no damge to your device.\n",
        "    Most laptops require between 19V and 20V DC output, with wattage ranging from 45W to 240W depending on the device class. And as long as they aren't targeted at powerusers or gamers.\n",
        "    Ultrabooks typically use 45W-65W adapters, gaming laptops require 150W-240W, and business laptops commonly use 65W-90W.\n",
        "    Using an adapter with lower wattage than specified can cause charging issues, performance throttling, or adapter overheating.\n",
        "    Higher wattage adapters are generally safe if voltage matches, as the laptop draws only the power it needs.\n",
        "    Voltage mismatch is dangerous,using 12V on a 19V requirement will prevent charging, while 24V on a 19V device risks permanent damage.\n",
        "    Always verify the voltage, amperage, and polarity markings on the original adapter's label before purchasing replacements.\n",
        "    The center-positive polarity is standard for most laptop connectors, but some manufacturers use center-negative configurations.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_2\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Connector Types and Compatibility]\n",
        "\n",
        "    Laptop power connectors vary significantly across manufacturers and models. Even though we've seen a shift to USB-C being more of a standard for charging.\n",
        "    Barrel connectors remain the most common, with diameters ranging from 3.0mm to 7.4mm and lengths from 5.0mm to 17.0mm.\n",
        "    The combination of outer diameter and inner pin size determines compatibility,two adapters with identical voltage can be incompatible due to connector differences.\n",
        "    USB-C Power Delivery has become standard for modern ultrabooks, supporting up to 100W (240W with USB-PD 3.1). And is making its way to more budget options.\n",
        "    Proprietary connectors continue to exist from manufacturers like Lenovo (rectangular tip), HP (blue ring indicator), and Dell (center pin with data communication).\n",
        "    When replacing adapters, measure the connector precisely using calipers if possible. Universal adapter kits with interchangeable tips can work but require careful tip selection.\n",
        "    Some adapters include smart pins that communicate with the laptop for battery optimization.These may trigger warnings if non-genuine adapters are used.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_3\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Safety Certifications and Standards]\n",
        "\n",
        "    All legitimate laptop adapters carry multiple safety certifications indicating compliance with regional electrical standards.\n",
        "    UL certification (Underwriters Laboratories) is required for US market sales, while CE marking indicates European conformity.\n",
        "    FCC certification ensures electromagnetic interference compliance. Additional certifications include TUV (Germany), CCC (China), and KC (Korea).\n",
        "    Certified adapters include proper insulation, surge protection, and thermal management systems.Counterfeit adapters most often lack these protections, creating fire hazards and risking laptop damage. So not recommended for those trying to stick to a tighter budget.\n",
        "    Look for certification marks printed clearly on the adapter housing, not just packaging.Most reputable manufacturers include original equipment manufacturers (OEM) like Delta Electronics, Lite-On, and Chicony, plus certified third-party brands like Anker and UGREEN.\n",
        "    Adapters should operate below 45°C under normal load. Overheating beyond 60°C indicates potential failure. All quality adapters should include short-circuit protection, over-voltage protection, and over-current protection as minimum safety features.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_4\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Common Troubleshooting Issues]\n",
        "\n",
        "    The most common laptop adapter problems stem from cable damage, connector wear, or power outlet issues.Frayed cables near the connector point are the most common failure mode,inspect regularly for exposed wiring. Also a good idea to keep your pets from chewing on the cable.\n",
        "    Loose connections causing intermittent charging often indicate worn barrel connectors or damaged laptop power jacks. If the adapter LED flickers or turns off during use, the internal transformer may be failing.\n",
        "    Adapter humming or buzzing sounds indicate coil whine, which can precede complete failure. Laptop not recognizing the adapter despite correct voltage suggests smart pin communication failure or motherboard power circuit damage.\n",
        "    Testing with a multimeter can verify output voltage stability under load. If voltage drops more than 5% when connected to the laptop, the adapter cannot supply sufficient current.\n",
        "    Cleaning the connector with compressed air removes dust causing poor contact. Replacing the adapter before complete failure prevents unexpected shutdowns during important work.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_5\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [USB-C Power Delivery Standards]\n",
        "\n",
        "    USB-C Power Delivery (PD) has revolutionized laptop charging with universal connectivity and intelligent power negotiation. USB-PD 2.0 supports up to 100W (20V at 5A), while USB-PD 3.1 extends to 240W (48V at 5A).\n",
        "    Laptops negotiate power profiles automatically with compatible chargers, selecting optimal voltage and current. Not all USB-C ports support power delivery. Some are data-only or video output only.\n",
        "    Charging speed depends on both charger capability and laptop acceptance rate. A 100W charger won't charge a laptop faster than its maximum input rating allows.\n",
        "    USB-C PD chargers can power multiple devices simultaneously if total wattage doesn't exceed capacity. Cable quality matters, E-Marker chips identify cables capable of carrying higher currents.\n",
        "    Cheap cables may only support 60W regardless of charger capability. Fast charging protocols like Qualcomm Quick Charge are incompatible with USB-PD.\n",
        "    For best results, use manufacturer-recommended USB-C PD chargers or certified third-party alternatives with matching wattage ratings.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_6\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Brand-Specific Adapter Requirements]\n",
        "\n",
        "    Different laptop manufacturers have unique adapter specifications requiring careful attention. Apple MacBook adapters use MagSafe magnetic connectors or USB-C PD, with wattage varying from 30W for MacBooks to 140W for MacBook Pros. Not only depening on the cable, but the wall adapter as well.\n",
        "    Dell uses proprietary barrel connectors with center data pins for battery optimization, third-party adapters may trigger warnings. HP employs blue-ring indicators on connectors and requires specific wattage for full performance.\n",
        "    Lenovo's rectangular connectors and square tips differ from traditional barrel designs. ASUS and Acer generally use standard barrel connectors but vary pin sizes significantly. Gaming laptops from MSI, Razer, and Alienware require high-wattage adapters (150W-330W) due to power-hungry components.\n",
        "    Using underspecified adapters causes performance throttling even if charging works. Always check the laptop model number against manufacturer documentation for exact adapter requirements. OEM adapters guarantee compatibility but cost more than third-party alternatives. And aren't always the best option for charging.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_7\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Replacement Guidelines and Selection]\n",
        "\n",
        "    When selecting replacement laptop adapters, prioritize exact specification matching over brand loyalty. Essential parameters include output voltage (must match exactly), output amperage (equal or higher acceptable), connector dimensions (precise fit required), and polarity (typically center-positive).\n",
        "    Calculate minimum wattage by multiplying voltage times amperage from the original adapter label. Consider future laptop purchases, universal adapters with multiple tips offer flexibility but may lack reliability.\n",
        "    Budget allocation should prioritize safety certifications over price savings where applicable. Quality adapters last 3-5 years under normal use, while cheap alternatives fail within months and have higher risk of damaging your device. Purchase from authorized retailers to avoid counterfeit products.\n",
        "    Keep all original packaging and receipts for warranty claims. Some manufacturers offer adapter warranties extending beyond the laptop warranty period. For business environments, maintain spare adapters to minimize downtime.\n",
        "    Document adapter specifications for each device in your inventory for quick replacement ordering.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    \"document_8\": \"\"\"\n",
        "    [Warranty and Return Policies]\n",
        "\n",
        "    Laptop adapter warranties typically range from 90 days to 3 years depending on manufacturer and purchase channel. OEM adapters from laptop manufacturers usually carry 1-year warranties matching the laptop coverage.\n",
        "    Third-party adapter warranties vary widely. Reputable brands offer 2-3 year coverage while budget options provide minimal protection. Warranty claims require proof of purchase and often the original packaging.\n",
        "    Defects covered include manufacturing flaws, premature failure, and safety component failures. Damage from power surges, physical abuse, or improper voltage is typically excluded.\n",
        "    Return policies allow exchanges within 30 days for any reason at most retailers. Restocking fees may apply to opened electronics. Extended warranties purchased separately cover accidental damage but increase total cost.\n",
        "    Register products with manufacturers for streamlined warranty service. Keep serial numbers documented, many adapters have unique identifiers for warranty validation. International warranty coverage varies by brand. Some honor global warranties while others restrict service to region of purchase.\n",
        "    \"\"\",\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Add more documents as needed...\n",
        "}\n",
        "\n",
        "# Validation\n",
        "print(\"KNOWLEDGE BASE VALIDATION\")\n",
        "print(\"=\" * 50)\n",
        "print(f\"Total documents: {len(knowledge_base)}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "total_words = 0\n",
        "for doc_name, content in knowledge_base.items():\n",
        "    word_count = len(content.split())\n",
        "    total_words += word_count\n",
        "    status = \"Pass\" if word_count >= 150 else \"Too short!\"\n",
        "    print(f\"  {doc_name}: {word_count} words {status}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"\\nTotal words: {total_words}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Average words per document: {total_words // len(knowledge_base)}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "if len(knowledge_base) >= 8:\n",
        "    print(\"\\nDocument count requirement met!\")\n",
        "else:\n",
        "    print(f\"\\nYou need at least 8 documents. Currently have: {len(knowledge_base)}\")"
      ],
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": [
